1. Verdict: `CONDITIONAL`

2. Findings

1. Severity: `high`; category: `bootstrap mismatch`. File evidence: [README.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/README.md), [docs/ADOPTION_GUIDE.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/ADOPTION_GUIDE.md), [scripts/bootstrap_adoption.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/scripts/bootstrap_adoption.py), [scripts/validate_template.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/scripts/validate_template.py). Why it matters: the recommended `standard` profile ships `README.md` and `docs/ADOPTION_GUIDE.md`, but those docs still link or point users to `examples/demo_project/...`, [`examples/skills/`](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/examples/skills), and [`examples/full_stack_project/`](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/examples/full_stack_project), which `bootstrap_adoption.py` only copies in `full`. Adopted-repo validation then skips doc-link checks, so a standard-profile repo can validate green while carrying broken profile-local guidance. Smallest honest fix: mark those references as `full`-profile-only in the docs or move the referenced assets into `standard`; also run profile-local doc-link validation for adopted repos.

2. Severity: `high`; category: `rule-execution gap`. File evidence: [docs/ADOPTION_GUIDE.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/ADOPTION_GUIDE.md), [scripts/bootstrap_adoption.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/scripts/bootstrap_adoption.py), [scripts/validate_template.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/scripts/validate_template.py). Why it matters: the guide says “If the relevant runtime path depends on a build step, also declare `Build`,” but the shipped manifest/validator contract hard-requires a `Build` surface in `required_surface_kinds` for adopted repos. An adopter can follow the guide literally and still fail the validator. Smallest honest fix: change the docs and template wording to “always include a `Build` row; use `none` when truly not applicable,” which matches the actual validator contract.

3. Severity: `medium`; category: `validator blind spot`. File evidence: [docs/SKILL_EXECUTION_LAYER_V1_DRAFT.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/SKILL_EXECUTION_LAYER_V1_DRAFT.md), [docs/ADOPTION_GUIDE.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/ADOPTION_GUIDE.md), [scripts/validate_template.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/scripts/validate_template.py), [templates/skill_tool_wrapper.template.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/templates/skill_tool_wrapper.template.md), [templates/skill_reviewer_gate.template.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/templates/skill_reviewer_gate.template.md), [templates/skill_pipeline.template.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/templates/skill_pipeline.template.md), [templates/skill_artifact_generator.template.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/templates/skill_artifact_generator.template.md). Why it matters: upper-layer docs describe these starters as validator-visible, structurally truthful execution scaffolds, but the validator only checks for a few literal bullet snippets plus generic SKILL headings. It does not verify the actual pattern-specific promises: wrapper bound to a declared toolchain surface, reviewer tied to a real verdict sink, pipeline tied to a real handoff artifact, generator tied to a schema-backed artifact family. Smallest honest fix: add a small set of pattern-specific assertions against the starter references already shipped.

4. Severity: `medium`; category: `example drift`. File evidence: [docs/ADOPTION_GUIDE.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/ADOPTION_GUIDE.md), [examples/skills/03_developer_toolchain_wrapper.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/examples/skills/03_developer_toolchain_wrapper.md), [examples/skills/04_receipt_anchored_reviewer.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/examples/skills/04_receipt_anchored_reviewer.md), [examples/skills/05_staged_handoff_pipeline.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/examples/skills/05_staged_handoff_pipeline.md), [examples/skills/06_bounded_artifact_generator.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/examples/skills/06_bounded_artifact_generator.md). Why it matters: the guide still says the “current starter set covers one `workflow` skill and one `guardrail` skill,” which is no longer true after the five-pattern wave. That understates the shipped lower layer and makes the new examples look unofficial or absent. Smallest honest fix: update that sentence to enumerate the six shipped examples and note that 03-06 are the new scaffold wave.

5. Severity: `low`; category: `test gap`. File evidence: [tests/test_bootstrap_adoption.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/tests/test_bootstrap_adoption.py), [tests/test_validate_template.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/tests/test_validate_template.py). Why it matters: tests prove bootstrap and validation pass, but they do not assert profile-aware doc integrity or the docs-to-manifest `Build` contract. That is why the mismatches above can survive green CI. Smallest honest fix: add one standard-profile smoke test for markdown-link resolution inside the adopted repo and one assertion that adoption-doc wording matches the manifest-required `Build` surface.

3. Residual risks

- Even after these fixes, validator coverage remains structural, not semantic. A repository can still ship low-quality skills that satisfy headings and tables.
- The execution-layer proof is strongest for invocation/candidate artifact generation, not for real host-runtime invocation quality. Repeated-use evolution can still be overstated by adopters if they treat templates as operational automation.
- Profile-specific docs can drift again unless link checks and profile-aware content checks run on adopted repos, not just on the template root.

4. Final recommendation: `accept-with-fixes`
